---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .migration-chip-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr)); gap: 6px; margin-top: 12px; }
    .migration-chip {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11.5px;
      padding: 6px 9px;
      background: var(--muted);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: 4px;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
    }
    .stat-row { display: flex; gap: 24px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 12px; }
    .stat-pill {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 14px 18px;
      background: var(--card);
      min-width: 160px;
    }
    .stat-pill .stat-num { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 600; font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    .stat-pill .stat-label { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text-muted); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; margin-top: 4px; }
    table.data td code { white-space: nowrap; }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="05 · Database Schema — Sardis Canvas" currentId="database">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 05 · Backend</span>
        <h1>Database Schema</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          One Neon Postgres database. 107 sequentially-numbered SQL migrations under
          <code>packages/server-api/migrations/</code>. No ORM is doing the heavy lifting — tables are
          defined by hand, in SQL, and applied in strict order. When Postgres is the source of truth for
          money, legibility beats abstraction.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          Migrations are the canonical record of how the schema evolved. Reading them in order is the
          fastest way to understand what Sardis does: identity first, then wallets, then policies, then
          ledger, then merchants, then mandates, then protocol-specific tables (Tempo, A2A, x402),
          and finally the <code>ba_</code>-prefixed better-auth surface.
        </div>
        <div class="stat-row">
          <div class="stat-pill"><div class="stat-num">107</div><div class="stat-label">Migrations</div></div>
          <div class="stat-pill"><div class="stat-num">Neon</div><div class="stat-label">Postgres, serverless</div></div>
          <div class="stat-pill"><div class="stat-num">50+</div><div class="stat-label">Tables</div></div>
          <div class="stat-pill"><div class="stat-num">NNN_*.sql</div><div class="stat-label">Naming convention</div></div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Conventions -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Conventions</div>
          <h2>How this schema is written.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Hand-written SQL, applied in order</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Migrations live in <code>packages/server-api/migrations/</code> as
              <code>NNN_description.sql</code>. Applied with
              <code>psql $DATABASE_URL -f &lt;file&gt;</code>. A <code>schema_migrations</code> table guards
              against double-apply. No Alembic, no Django, no Drizzle — direct SQL keeps the diff honest.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Append-only, additive-only</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Destructive changes (drop column, tighten constraint) must be proposed as a new migration with
              a rollback companion (see <code>001_initial_schema_rollback.sql</code>). <code>ADD COLUMN IF
              NOT EXISTS</code> is used liberally so migrations are re-runnable on partially-applied dbs.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Three primary-key styles, chosen on purpose</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>uuid</code> for records a human might quote (orgs, wallets, merchants). <code>text</code>
              prefixed IDs (<code>mandate_…</code>, <code>appr_…</code>, <code>mst_…</code>) for records an
              agent or operator will handle. <code>bigserial</code> only for high-churn internal queues
              (<code>reconciliation_queue</code>).
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title"><code>ba_</code> prefix for better-auth tables</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              The better-auth library manages its own schema (<code>ba_user</code>, <code>ba_session</code>,
              <code>ba_apikey</code>, …) and coexists with legacy Sardis auth tables. Prefix avoids
              collisions while the dual-path is live. See migrations 077, 097, 098.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Indexes travel with the columns that need them</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Every migration that adds a frequently-queried column also adds the index. Migration 087
              (<code>missing_indexes</code>) exists to clean up what slipped through. Query plans stay
              predictable.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">JSONB for open-ended, columns for load-bearing</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>metadata</code>, <code>settings</code>, <code>merchant_scope</code> are JSONB because
              shape evolves. Money columns (<code>amount_per_tx</code>, <code>spent_total</code>) are
              <code>NUMERIC(20,6)</code> because floats in finance cost real money.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ER diagram -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Core shape</div>
          <h2>ER diagram — the payment spine.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            A simplified entity map of the tables every money-moving request touches. Ownership flows left
            to right; evidence flows right to left.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
erDiagram
    organizations ||--o{ agents : "owns"
    organizations ||--o{ ba_user : "has members"
    organizations ||--o{ merchants : "operates"
    agents ||--o{ wallets : "controls"
    agents ||--o{ agent_group_members : "joins"
    agent_groups ||--o{ agent_group_members : "groups"
    agents ||--o{ spending_policies : "is governed by"
    spending_policies ||--o{ policy_versions : "has history"
    agents ||--o{ spending_mandates : "is delegated"
    spending_mandates ||--o{ mandate_state_transitions : "audit log"
    spending_mandates ||--o{ spending_mandates : "parent of"
    spending_mandates ||--o{ policy_decisions : "produces"
    policy_versions ||--o{ policy_decisions : "evaluates"
    wallets ||--o{ transactions : "submits"
    transactions ||--o{ receipts : "settles into"
    transactions ||--o{ ledger_entries : "records"
    ledger_entries ||--o{ merkle_batches : "rolls up into"
    merchants ||--o{ merchant_checkout_sessions : "sells via"
    merchant_checkout_sessions ||--o{ transactions : "settles through"
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Migration timeline — representative -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Timeline</div>
          <h2>Representative migrations — read these to understand the system.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            20 migrations sampled from the full 107. Each one corresponds to a real product moment; reading
            them in order is the fastest onboarding you can do as a backend engineer.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>#</th><th>Name</th><th>What it added</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>001</code></td><td><code>initial_schema</code></td><td>Organizations, agents — the tenancy root. Rollback companion ships alongside.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>002</code></td><td><code>spending_policy_state</code></td><td><code>spent_total</code> on <code>spending_policies</code>; multi-token <code>time_window_limits</code>. First enforceable spending limits.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>003</code></td><td><code>ledger_compliance_tables</code></td><td>Promotes ledger <code>receipts</code> and compliance tables from runtime <code>CREATE IF NOT EXISTS</code> into durable SQL.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>004</code></td><td><code>approvals</code></td><td>Human-in-the-loop approval queue with <code>approval_status</code> enum (pending / approved / denied / expired / cancelled).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>013</code></td><td><code>ledger_merkle_receipts</code></td><td>Merkle batching for ledger evidence — the foundation for on-chain anchors.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>014</code></td><td><code>agent_groups</code></td><td>Multi-agent governance — group-level budget (per-tx, daily, monthly, total) and <code>agent_group_members</code> linkage.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>017</code></td><td><code>erc4337_wallet_fields</code></td><td>Adds smart-account / user-op / entry-point columns on <code>wallets</code> for Safe v1.4.1 upgrade.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>019</code></td><td><code>canonical_ledger_state</code></td><td>Canonicalizes the state machine — every payment moves through the same FSM regardless of rail.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>030</code></td><td><code>merchant_checkout</code></td><td>"Pay with Sardis" — <code>merchants</code>, <code>merchant_checkout_sessions</code>, settlement preferences (USDC / fiat).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>031</code></td><td><code>checkout_hardening</code></td><td>client_secret, idempotency_key (unique index), platform_fee_amount, embed_origin, reusable checkout links, webhook delivery dedup.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>037</code></td><td><code>durable_idempotency</code></td><td>Idempotency-key storage promoted from Redis to Postgres for durability guarantees.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>040</code></td><td><code>policy_versions</code></td><td>Immutable version records for every policy change — <code>policy_json</code>, <code>hash</code>, <code>parent_version_id</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>041</code></td><td><code>policy_decisions</code></td><td>Evidence log — every <code>evaluate()</code> produces a signed decision (<code>verdict</code>, <code>steps_json</code>, <code>evidence_hash</code>) for SOC 2.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>056</code></td><td><code>erc8183_jobs</code></td><td>Job queue for ERC-8183 policy-guard on-chain enforcement.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>057</code></td><td><code>reconciliation_queue</code></td><td>Persistent recon queue — replaces in-memory implementation so pending ledger appends survive restarts.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>071</code></td><td><code>spending_mandates</code></td><td>Core spending-mandate table — principal, issuer, merchant_scope, amount_&#123;per_tx, daily, weekly, monthly, total&#125;, lifecycle enum.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>072</code></td><td><code>mandate_transitions</code></td><td>Audit log of every lifecycle change (activate, suspend, revoke, expire) keyed to <code>spending_mandates.id</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>074</code></td><td><code>tempo_support</code></td><td>TIP-20 gas model — <code>memo</code>, <code>fee_token</code>, <code>fee_token_amount</code>, <code>tip20_transfer</code> on <code>transactions</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>077</code></td><td><code>better_auth_tables</code></td><td><code>ba_user</code>, <code>ba_session</code>, <code>ba_account</code>, <code>ba_verification</code> — session-based auth path.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>080</code></td><td><code>mandate_trees</code></td><td>Hierarchical mandate delegation — <code>parent_mandate_id</code>, <code>delegation_depth</code>, <code>root_mandate_id</code>. CFO → dept → agent.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>085</code></td><td><code>a2a_tables</code></td><td>Google A2A — <code>settlements</code> and <code>escrows</code> tables for agent-to-agent commerce.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>097</code></td><td><code>ba_apikey_table</code></td><td>better-auth API-key plugin table — hashed key, rate-limit fields, permissions JSONB, mode (live / test).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>106</code></td><td><code>agent_registry</code></td><td>Public agent directory — <code>capabilities</code>, <code>supported_protocols</code>, <code>trust_score</code>, <code>kya_status</code>.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

